      devanagari: 'समदुःखसुखः स्वस्थः समलोष्टाश्मकाञ्चनः ।\nतुल्यप्रियाप्रियो धीरस्तुल्यनिन्दात्मसंस्तुतिः ॥',
      transliteration: 'sama-duḥkha-sukhaḥ sva-sthaḥ sama-loṣṭāśma-kāñcanaḥ\ntulya-priyāpriyo dhīras tulya-nindātma-saṁstutiḥ',
      translation: 'Equal in pain and pleasure, established in the Self; equal toward a clod of earth, a stone, and gold; the same toward the pleasant and unpleasant; steady, equal in blame and in praise of oneself —',
      words: [
        { word: 'sama-duḥkha-sukhaḥ', meaning: 'equal in pain and pleasure / the same in joy and sorrow' },
        { word: 'sva-sthaḥ', meaning: 'established in the Self / resting in one\'s own nature / literally "standing in oneself"' },
        { word: 'sama-loṣṭa-aśma-kāñcanaḥ', meaning: 'equal toward a clod, stone, and gold / seeing the same in earth, rock, and gold' },
        { word: 'tulya-priya-apriyaḥ', meaning: 'equal toward the pleasant and unpleasant / the same toward what is liked and disliked' },
        { word: 'dhīraḥ', meaning: 'steady / courageous / grounded / resolute' },
        { word: 'tulya-nindā-ātma-saṁstutiḥ', meaning: 'equal toward blame and praise / the same when criticized as when praised' }
      ],
      commentary: `The portrait of the guṇātīta continues with a series of "samā" — equalities. Equal in pain and pleasure. Equal toward a clod of earth and gold. Equal when praised and when condemned. This is not emotional flatness or indifference — it is the stability of someone whose inner security does not depend on external circumstances.\n\nSva-sthaḥ — established in the Self. The word means literally "standing in one's own" — one who has their foundation in what they actually are rather than in the fluctuating contents of their experience. This is the key. The equanimity described in this verse is not achieved by suppressing the preference for pleasure over pain. It arises naturally when the locus of being shifts from the field to the knower of the field. What happens in the field matters; it just no longer determines the stability of the one who witnesses it.\n\nSama-loṣṭāśma-kāñcanaḥ — equal to a clod of earth, a stone, and gold. This famous image points to the dissolution of the value-hierarchies that make equanimity impossible for most people. We organize our world according to which things have value — gold matters, a clod does not. When the divine is seen equally present in all, the gold and the clod are both expressions of the same reality. Not that they have equal market value — obviously not. But their nature is the same, and the one who sees that is no longer enslaved by the differential.`,
      youtubeShort: { title: 'The Mind That Reacts to Everything Loses Peace | Bhagavad Gita 14.24', url: 'https://www.youtube.com/shorts/rClSFni1cBE' }
