      transliteration: 'mānāpamānayos tulyas tulyo mitrāri-pakṣayoḥ\nsarvārambha-parityāgī guṇātītaḥ sa ucyate',
      translation: 'Equal in honor and dishonor; the same toward the party of friends as toward enemies; having renounced all undertakings — that one is said to have transcended the guṇas.',
      words: [
        { word: 'māna-apamānayoḥ tulyaḥ', meaning: 'equal in honor and dishonor / the same when honored or dishonored' },
        { word: 'tulyaḥ mitra-ari-pakṣayoḥ', meaning: 'equal toward the party of friends and enemies / the same with allies as opponents' },
        { word: 'sarva-ārambha-parityāgī', meaning: 'having renounced all undertakings / abandoned all ego-motivated initiations' },
        { word: 'guṇātītaḥ saḥ ucyate', meaning: 'that one is said to have transcended the guṇas / is called the one beyond the three modes' }
      ],
      commentary: `The description of the guṇātīta culminates here with a final set of equalities and one crucial action: sarvārambha-parityāgī — having renounced all undertakings. This does not mean having stopped all activity. It means having relinquished all ego-motivated initiations — all the projects that are secretly about proving something, getting something, or becoming something. Action continues; the attachment to launching and owning the action dissolves.\n\nTulyo mitrāri-pakṣayoḥ — the same toward the party of friends and enemies. This one is stark. Not treating everyone with identical behavior regardless of context, but having the same quality of inner regard — the same basic recognition of the divine presence in all — regardless of whether that person is ally or opponent. Equanimity toward enemies does not mean abandoning discrimination; it means not allowing hatred to distort your fundamental perception of the other as a being in whom the same presence dwells.\n\nGuṇātītaḥ sa ucyate — that one is said to have gone beyond the guṇas. After all the verses of description, the chapter finally names the state: guṇātīta, "beyond the guṇas." Not anti-guṇa, not without guṇas, but beyond them — meaning the identity is no longer located in any particular guṇa configuration. The guṇas continue their play; the witness is no longer caught in it.`
