      devanagari: 'मां च योऽव्यभिचारेण भक्तियोगेन सेवते ।\nस गुणान्समतीत्यैतान्ब्रह्मभूयाय कल्पते ॥',
      transliteration: 'māṁ ca yo \'vyabhicāreṇa bhakti-yogena sevate\nsa guṇān samatītyaitān brahma-bhūyāya kalpate',
      translation: 'One who serves me with the yoga of exclusive, unwavering devotion — having transcended these guṇas — becomes fit for Brahman.',
      words: [
        { word: 'mām ca yaḥ avyabhicāreṇa', meaning: 'one who serves me without straying / who worships me exclusively' },
        { word: 'bhakti-yogena sevate', meaning: 'serves with the yoga of devotion / worships through bhakti-yoga' },
        { word: 'saḥ guṇān samatītya etān', meaning: 'having completely transcended these guṇas / going fully beyond all three modes' },
        { word: 'brahma-bhūyāya kalpate', meaning: 'becomes fit for Brahman / is qualified for Brahman-nature / is prepared to become Brahman' }
      ],
      commentary: `Arjuna asked at verse 21: how does one transcend the guṇas? The answer arrives here, and it is not another guṇa-management technique. It is bhakti-yoga — the yoga of exclusive, unwavering devotion. Avyabhicāreṇa — not straying to other things. The devotion that transcends the guṇas is not casual or intermittent. It is the orientation of an entire life toward the divine.\n\nWhy does bhakti transcend the guṇas? Because the guṇas operate at the level of Prakṛti — they are the threads of material nature. Devotion oriented toward the divine reaches toward what is beyond Prakṛti entirely. Every act of genuine devotion is a movement toward the kṣetrajña, the witness, the presence beyond all guṇas. The devotee who repeatedly orients toward the divine gradually comes to rest in the divine, which is precisely the guṇātīta state.\n\nBrahma-bhūyāya kalpate — becomes fit for Brahman. The word brahma-bhūya means "Brahman-becoming" — not merely approaching Brahman but becoming Brahman, becoming what one essentially is. The fitting or qualification (kalpate) implies a process, not an instant — the devotion prepares the ground, removes the obscurations, orients the consciousness, until the recognition can arise fully. Bhakti and jñāna, love and knowledge, are not separate paths. Bhakti is the path into the recognition that jñāna describes.`
