      commentary: `The chapter closes with one of the most profound declarations in the entire Gita. I am the pratiṣṭhā — the foundation, the abode — of Brahman itself. This seems paradoxical: how can the personal divine be the ground of the impersonal Brahman? The Gita's answer is that the personal and impersonal are not two separate realities but two aspects of one reality, and the personal aspect (Krishna, the divine presence in relationship) is the deeper ground that makes even the impersonal conceivable.\n\nAmṛtasya avyayasya — the immortal, the imperishable. These are qualities of Brahman that the chapter has been pointing toward. And the divine says: I am their ground. The deathlessness that the liberated one attains is not something other than the divine's own nature. When you touch immortality, you are touching what Krishna is. When you rest in the imperishable, you are resting in what Krishna is.\n\nSukhasyaikāntikasya — absolute happiness. Ekāntika means unconditional, one-pointed, exclusive. Not the happiness that depends on circumstances — that comes and goes with the guṇas. The ultimate happiness that is Brahman's own nature, the bliss (ānanda) that is one of the three faces of Brahman in the Upaniṣadic formula sat-cit-ānanda. This is where the chapter ends: not with a technique or a warning but with an affirmation. The ground of all that is real — Brahman, amṛta, eternal dharma, ultimate happiness — is the divine itself. And that divine is available to you, through bhakti, through jñāna, through the sustained orientation of your entire life toward what is most real.`
